# Why People Hate Systems (And How to Change It)

It seems everyone hates systems. The problems are everywhere:

* You call technical support for an issue with your computer, waiting for hours on hold because the technician doesn’t have the authority to solve your problem.

* You walk into a business and fill out a copious amount of paperwork for a minor project.

* You work at an organization with such an extensive paper trail, you can’t get any meaningful work done, and your boss requires you to report every small detail back to him.

Many people consider systems to be restrictive and counterproductive. However, it’s not systems that people hate.

**What people hate are *broken* systems.** People hate systems that interfere with whatever they’re *supposed* to do, that keep them from doing meaningful work.

## What Makes People Love a System

People will love systems that make their life easier. Those systems always reflect what people should naturally do.

When they’re implemented correctly, they free you and your employees from making unnecessary decisions and correcting needless mistakes. They can eliminate all the busywork and guesswork so your employees can focus on the work that matters.

Good systems can move you from juggling a hundred machetes to tinkering on a well-oiled machine. With good systems in place, you can:

* Stop worrying about getting paid by your customers  
* Stop worrying that you’ll run out of inventory  
* Stop worrying whether your employees are trained to do their job  
* Stop worrying about weekly deposits making their way to the bank  
* Stop worrying about vendors calling you about a lost invoice  
* Stop worrying about customers complaining about inconsistencies in what you deliver

That’s the power of a good system.

## What Keeps the System Alive

However, it’s not enough to simply “create and forget”.

Healthy organizations are continually growing and adapting to new requirements. If your organization grows faster than your systems, you will constantly be fighting with out-of-date, unreasonable systems that get in the way.

You not only need to create systems that fit your business workflow, but you must create a way to continually improve those systems. When you do that, you can create a culture in your business that not only accepts systems but *embraces them* because they are valuable.

What are systems that you need to fix, or maybe even implement? Do that now, because the health and productivity of your business depends on that.
